[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     96[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m1[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mThe disenrollment-rationale validator has unique stakes.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m When the deterministic policy recommends disenrollment, the LLM-generated rationale is the document a clinical lead reads before deciding whether to disenroll the patient. A rationale that omits a countervailing factor (e.g., the patient just had a clinical event that explains the engagement decline; the patient's care manager went on leave for two of the four missed contacts; the patient's preferred modality was incorrectly set), or that confidently cites a policy-rule trigger that doesn't actually apply, can lead a busy clinical lead to approve a disenrollment that should not have happened. The validator must enforce that every cited engagement-history fact appears in [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mobserved_context.engagement_history[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, every cited clinical event appears in [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mobserved_context.recent_clinical_events[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, and the cited [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mpolicy_rule[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m matches the deterministic policy's actual triggering rule (not a hallucinated rule name).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     97[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
